 {
    "response_text": "The mean habit factor for whole milk begins at a neutral value of 1.00 at time step 0. At step 1, the metric exhibits a sharp discontinuous increase to approximately 1.02 across all simulation runs, reflecting the immediate activation of habitual mechanisms once agents begin processing their initial consumption decisions. Following this initial jump, the habit factor demonstrates a steady, approximately linear upward trajectory throughout the remainder of the simulation period, reaching values between 1.044 and 1.055 by step 32. \n\nThis progressive strengthening of the habit multiplier suggests that agents who maintain whole milk consumption experience increasing habitual reinforcement over time, as repeated choices strengthen the neural and behavioral pathways associated with the incumbent option. The rate of increase remains relatively constant at approximately 0.001 per time step after the initial activation phase.\n\nThe simulation runs display minimal variance during the first 5 time steps, with trajectories tightly clustered around the mean. However, beginning around step 8-10, the individual runs begin to diverge progressively, with the spread between the lowest and highest trajectories expanding to approximately 0.015 by the final time step. This growing divergence indicates that stochastic elements in the social network interactions and individual decision-making processes generate increasingly heterogeneous habit strength outcomes across different simulation realizations. The lower bound of the final distribution (approximately 1.044) represents simulation runs where social influence and changing perceptions may have slowed the habitual reinforcement process, while the upper bound (approximately 1.055) reflects runs where network effects and individual psychology combined to produce stronger habit maintenance among whole milk consumers."
}

